Application of ComBat-seq on simulated dataset

biological & batch effects

Yuqing Zhang

September 25, 2018

Design of the study

We simulated a (2000 gene \(\times\) 20 sample) count matrix from negative binomial distribution. The dataset contains 2 batches, with 10 samples in each batch, and biological effect - a 2-fold change. This is still an idealistic example: 1) batch affects all genes (in the same gene group) in the same way, 2) genes have common mean and dispersion.

Simulate dataset

Distribution of counts in samples

Library sizes (average counts in each sample) are roughly similar across batches. The biologically activated samples have larger library size than the control samples. The dispersion parameters are different in two batches (Batch B: 0.05, Batch A: 0.01).

Batch effect in the dataset

However, genes are systematically different between the two batches. The first 1000 genes are higher in Batch A, while the next 1000 genes are have larger counts in Batch B. The image in the first tab below shows 10 genes from each gene group.

In the second tab, we show hiearachical clustering of samples in the dataset based on the unadjusted counts. Samples are clearly clustered by batch.

Counts in genes

Clustering of samples before adjustment

Apply ComBat-seq

Adjustment output

Visualize adjusted data

Similar as above, we visualize the adjusted counts in each sample (first tab), and in 10 genes from each gene group (second tab). Also, in the third tab, we can see that after the ComBat-seq adjustment, samples are no longer clustered by batch.

Thoughts

  • We do have a computational problem when the total number of genes reach 20000. Need to optimize the algorithm.
